Analysis of ETI Data

Growth Protocol for human cells

Human primary airway epithelial cells were grown in BronchiaLife basal medium (Lifeline Cell Technology, Frederick, MD, Cat. #LM-0007) supplemented with the BronchiaLife B/T LifeFactors Kit (Lifeline Cell Technology, Cat. #LS-1047) and penicillin (10,000 U/mL) and streptomycin (10,000 g/mL) (Sigma-Aldrich, Cat. #P4333). 500,000 cells were seeded on 24-mm permeable supports (Corning, Corning, NY, Cat. #3407), coated with Collagen type IV (Sigma-Aldrich, Cat #C-7521) and grown in an air-liquid interface media (University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill, NC) at 37C for 3 to 4 weeks to establish polarized monolayers.

Growth Protocol for Bacteria

Pseudomonas aeruginosa strain PA14 was grown in artificial sputum medium (ASM) then centrifuged, washed, and resuspended in fresh ASM before measuring the optical density at 600 nm (OD600) to determine number of bacteria.

Outer Membrane Vesicles

Outer membrane vesicles (bEVs) were prepared by centrifuging cultures at 2,800 g and 4 degrees C for 1 h to pellet bacteria. Supernatants were filtered twice through 0.45 m PVDF membrane filters (Millipore, Billerica, MA) then concentrated to approximately 200 L by centrifugation in 30 K Amicon filters (Millipore, Billerica, MA) at 2,800 g and 4 C. Concentrates were resuspended in buffer (20 mM HEPES, 500 mM NaCl, pH 7.4) and ultracentrifuged 2 h at 39,000 g and 4 C to pellet bEVs, which were resuspended in 60% OptiPrep Density Gradient Medium (Sigma-Aldrich, Cat. No.D1556) and layered with 40%, 35%, 30%, and 20% OptiPrep diluted in buffer. bEVs in OptiPrep layers were ultacentrifuged for 16 h at 100,000 g and 4 C. Fractions (500 L) were taken from the top of the gradient, with bEVs residing in fractions 23, corresponding to 25% OptiPrep. The purified bEVs were quantified by nanoparticle tracking analysis (NTA, NanoSight NS300, Malvern Panalytical Ltd, Malvern, UK)

Wild type cell exposures

Polarized human primary airway epithelial cells from donors with wild type CFTR were conditionally exposed to either Pseudomonas aeruginosa strain PA14 at a multiplicity of infection of 20:1(~2x10^7 bacteria) or 2e10 outer membrane vesicles (bEV) isolated from Pseudomonas aeruginosa strain PA14 for 6 hours, or media only as a control.

CF cell expoosures

Polarized human primary airway epithelial cells from donors homozygous for the delta F 508 CFTR mutation were conditionally exposed to elexacaftor (3 micromolar) tezacaftor (3 micromolar) ivacaftor (10 nanomolar) dissolved in DMSO or DMSO as a control for 48 hours and then conditionally exposed to either Pseudomonas aeruginosa strain PA14 at a multiplicity of infection of 20:1 (~2x10^7 bacteria) or 2e10 outer membrane vesicles (bEV) isolated from Pseudomonas aeruginosa strain PA14 for 6 hours, or media only as a control.

Read in, and interpret, meta-data

The original sample annotation is a little hard to follow. For example. it includes Control OMVs which does not (one hopes) contain outer membrane vesicles, but rather media that was processed the same way one would process outer membrane vesicles lots of centrifugation. We call this special blank the process control, or PC for short.


MetaRaw <- read_excel("../metadata.xlsx", skip = 2)
RawMetaFields <- strsplit(MetaRaw$`External Name`, split = " ")


# Process meta data
Meta <- data.frame("Sample" = MetaRaw$Id, "Desc" = MetaRaw$`External Name`)
rownames(Meta) <- Meta$Sample

Meta$Donor <- sapply(RawMetaFields, "[[", 2)
Meta$Geno <- sapply(RawMetaFields, "[[", 1)

Meta$Pathogen <- sapply(RawMetaFields, function (f){
  if (f[1] == "WT" & length (f)  == 3){
    f[3]
  } else if (f[1] == "WT" & length (f)  == 4 & f[3] == "Control"){
    "PC"
  } else if (f[1] == "WT" & length (f)  == 4 & f[3] == "PA14") {
    "OMV"
  } else if (f[1] == "dF" & length (f)  == 4) {
    f[3]
  } else if (f[1] == "dF" & length (f)  == 5 & f[3] == "Control"){
   "PC"
  } else if (f[1] == "dF" & length (f)  == 5 & f[3] == "PA14") {
   "OMV"
  } else{
    paste(f, collapse = '.')
  }
})

Meta$Rx <- NULL

Meta$Rx <-sapply(RawMetaFields, function (f){
  if (f[1] == "dF"){
    f[length(f)]
  } else {
    "Control"
  }
})

write.csv(Meta, file = "Meta.csv")

Subset the data for ETI only

Only CF cells were exposed to ETI, and for this paper, we are only concerned with the simple question of what ETI does (if anything) to gene expression. Looking at things this way can reduce power (though it might not) because each of 5 donors will be observed in only two conditions: with and without ETI.


ETI_Samples <- Meta[Meta$Geno == "dF" & Meta$Pathogen == "Control", "Sample" ]

ETI_meta <- Meta[colnames(ETI_counts), ]

Ingenuity

The Canonical Pathways tab displays the most significant Canonical Pathways across the entire dataset and across multiple datasets when you are reviewing a Comparison Analysis. IPA uses the p-value of overlap, calculated using the right-tailed Fishers Exact Test, to identify significant pathways. The significance indicates the probability of association of molecules from your dataset with the canonical pathway by random chance alone. If you would like to see Canonical Pathways that are associated with a particular network, see the Overlay Canonical Pathways section.

# List to store the generated formulas
all_formulas <- vector(length = length(Target.Names), mode = "character")

for (i in seq_along(Target.Names)) {
  # Replace "DEFB1" with the current column name in the formula template
  all_formulas[i] <- gsub("DEFB1", Target.Names[i], base_formula)

lapply(Target.Names, function (t) {
  F = as.data.frame(d.All.L[d.All.L$Gene %in% c(t, "Ref"), ])
  average_data <- average_by_modulator(F)
  average_data$Donor = "Mean"
  average_data$Gene <- factor(average_data$Gene, levels = c(t, "Ref"))
  
  # how to select 
  ggplot(F[F$Gene == t,], aes(x = Modulator, y = CT, color = Donor, shape = Gene)) +
  # Group by Gene and Donor for connecting lines
  geom_line(aes(group = interaction(Gene, Donor)), 
            linetype = "solid", linewidth = 1.5) +
  geom_point(size=4) +
  geom_point(data = average_data, aes(x=Modulator,y=mean_CT, shape = Gene,   group=Donor), inherit.aes = FALSE, size=5, show.legend = FALSE) +
  geom_line(data = average_data, aes(x=Modulator,y=mean_CT, group = interaction(Gene, Donor)), inherit.aes = FALSE,
            linewidth=1, linetype=2) +
  ggtitle(t) +
  theme_set(my_theme)
  ggsave(paste(t, "Panel.pdf", sep = '.'), width = 4, height = 4.5)
})

ELISA.FC <- lapply(names(E.Measurements), function (x){
  
  m <- E.Measurements[[x]]
  Donor <- m$ID[m$group == "MC ETI"]
  log2FC <- m$log2[m$group == "MC ETI"]  - m$log2[m$group == "MC DMSO"]
  Analyte <- sub("Paired_", "", x)
  data.frame("Analyte" = rep(Analyte, length(Donor)),
                                "Donor" = Donor,
                                "log2FC" = log2FC)
} )

ELISA.FC.Frame <- do.call(rbind, ELISA.FC)
ELISA.FC.Frame$Donor[ELISA.FC.Frame$Donor == "K18G"] <- "KK18G"
ELISA.FC.Frame$Cytokine <- sub("_B", "", ELISA.FC.Frame$Analyte)
